rComments: Lisa is so great. Engaging lectures. A privilege to be able to hear her speak.

Lisa Steele does an amazing job at engaging the class. Her first year lecture is intensive and requires a lot of memorization and study, but is extremely useful. Her upper year studio courses are equally interesting with guest speakers, gallery visits, and unconventional studio assignments. She is very constructive at critiques!

I have taken 3 classes from her. I had a really tough winter semester and ended up skipping out on my final critique and she was incredibly understanding and I still ended up with a B in her class. She is an iconic feminist video artist and gives constructive criticism, earning her approval is the best feeling in the world! I love you lisa!!!!!
Honestly a really bad start to semester 1 of my first year in university. She makes you memorize 500+ photos. Honestly pointless but needed the credit. Nice lady, not os nice prof.
get ready to memorize useless content in this useless mandatory course

tests are arguably easy but preparation requires a lot of useless memorization and time. The course itself is completely useless and the credit received for it is not worth the amount of work necessary for good grades.

Lectures are droning and boring. She records everything and posts it on blackboard so the best way to study is to listen to the lectures on repeat. Not approachable or understanding and is incredible strict about grading standards. (If you dont have her exact words, its wrong) Good luck, because shell make you memorize your whole $300 textbook.

Memorization components are easy but as someone previously said her lectures are spoken as if she is reading off a piece of paper. Dense and a bit monotonous. Also seems that her and her TA's don't have a clear guideline as to how things should be marked in the class. Topics discussed are interesting however.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: She is a great artist.

Her lecture was not that interesting mainly because of the way she spoke (like she was reading a paper) , but the contents were truly inspiring. Get ready to read and memorize artists, movements and etc. It was hard at first but once you mastered the memorization part and figured out the timeline of movements you would be 100% ready for the final.

Lots of studying. JAV120 is about memorization. Know the context she gives in class, then memorize images. Clear grading criteria and she really gives you ALL THE INFORMATION you need to do very well in her class.
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Test heavy', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: lectures lull you to sleep. Also, I really don't appreciate getting three extra lectures two days before the exam
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Yes, you need to memorize 700+ artworks (artist and movement) but if you pay attention and have any interest at all, that surprisingly isn't overly difficult. If you miss a class, all of that weeks images are online, as are recordings of the lecture, so don't worry about missing - Lisa is VERY organized. There is a textbook, but it's not required.
terrible

Okay, asking us to memorize 700+ works of art literally does nothing for you as a visual studies student. You can easily lose 10+ marks off a test for messing up the title or artist, so I don't know why she doesn't just ask for the movement which is more helpful. You don't need to go to tutorial, but they are helpful, my TA marked pretty average.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Clear grading criteria', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Have taken multiple courses with this professor. while VIS110 is brutally difficult, she becomes very clear, easy to understand and helpful in her smaller class sizes (second year and upwards). I believe the first year course is intended to be difficult because Visual studies' funding can only support so many students.
Lisa is good in a sense that she defines which art work is from which movement but it all becomes a blur once you have to memorize 700+ art works.

Lisa Steele made VIS120 practically impossible. We were asked to memorize over 700 pieces of modern art (not to mention over half of them look identical), lectures weren't engaging and tutorials were useless. Shame this course is necessary to continue into Visual Studies. Will probably have to change my major now.

Lisa writes up and reads off lecture notes. It's a little monotonous but it's also very well-written. Don't take if you hate modernism and radical avant-garde. TAs grade the assignments and tests.  Tests require a lot of memorization and analysis but it's definitely doable as long as you keep up with readings and go over artwork daily.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: I did not enjoyed her class at ALL. She was absolutely dull, spoke in a very monotone voice and her lectures were loaded with mostly random info. For the tests, you did not have to show an understanding of the subject, but just plain memorization. Tutorials were useless. She knows her stuff but did not transmit any interest to the students. BORING.

1. It's a hard course, *designed* to weed out students, because so many want to get in, and there are only so many places in VIS, because of its small budget. 2. This is U of T, not OCAD, so knowing and writing is pretty important. If you can't write, go to your college's Writing Centre. She's actually very supportive, but only has so much time.
Worst class ever had to change my major due to this class.

Horrible experience! Steele almost ruined my interests in visual art. 120 is a required course before enter the visual studies program and she gave us almost 200 pics per month to memorize (including title, artists, specific time, style). She is also a hard marker. The tutorials and T.As are USELESS at all.
incredible professor!

Lectures were very cluttered and she never answered my emails when I asked for feedback on my marked-reviews. The TA's are literally useless as well- one of mine made more spelling mistakes than a 3 month old monkey.

Terriable experience,more than 500 images to remember the title,date, artist and movement for the tests and the exam.Even Steele herself couldn't remember all.(She admitted during lecture) Dramatically,Steele is a famous video artist,which means: Steele requires something UNNECESSARY to become a good artist.(120 is required to the program BTW)

The class is very interesting she is able to get to the point and explain all the art movements. However, the tutorials are useless, the T.A's are advised not to help their students on essays, and the tutorials do not cover anything important from the lecture, its VERY random. Also, the professor is very dry and will only become chummy with a selec

Lectures elaborate on the readings, so do read (not skim) prior to lecture! Tutorials provided valuable information on what is expected on the exam. If you know your stuff, it will not be a problem to succeed. Have ready mini-essays on each movement.
Lots of memorizing, good lectures but she talks really fast making it hard to write down notes sometimes. Wouldn't be a good idea to miss class

Despite speaking very fast thus making it almost virtually impossible to take any notes, the class was very informative and helps a student understand modern art. I suggest you bring a recorder to class. Tutorials were not useful. Be prepared for hardcore memorization of slides.
terrible lecturer

Lisa Steele is very disorganized in the structure of her lectures. It is also in my experience that she advises her TA's to not help us with our essays, saying that because we're in University we should already be able to write, and that any help would be unfair . The course material is very interesting, but hindered by Lisa's poor teaching style.
Disorganized and inconsiderate towards students.  Does not finish basic items promised to students and tends to play favorites.
She was amazing.

If you can memorize the name, date (within 3 years), and time period of about 45 paintings and write all that down with a little summary of each within half an hour you won't have a problem. She's a nice lady and was willing to help, but is too focused on useless, often dull, details instead of any real understanding of art.
terrible lecturer. she reads the whole lecture off her notes, speaks in monotone and stutters a lot. very difficult to follow.  altogether ineffective.  she killed this course.
She is an amazing lecturer

A lovely woman and a thoughtful lecturer, but that course is a nightmare--meant to weed out anyone who can't remember 500 slides for one test.  Still, though, she knows her stuff and she's there for her students.

She actually said hello to me in the hallway, I didn't even know she knew I was in her class! Eventhough I still need to get used to the whole Modern "Art" thing :-/, She did clarify and organize the movements well.  Real nice Prof.!
I wish she had been there; she was often absent.
